{"id":14881023,"mediaExerciseId":"e99adecc-2d53-406a-9e94-183c455c6647","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"6","chapterTitle":"Discounted Cash Flow Valuation","groupId":612303,"groupTitle":"Minicase Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":194,"solutions":[{"id":6339612,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will compare whether using the future value of an investment is better compared to using the present value.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"When evaluating an investment using its future value, we need to know the future flow of cash in order to make the right calculations. Compared to the present value where the only values that are needed are the cost of choosing an option and its possible pay offs.\n\nMoreover, it will be inaccurate if we compare the future value of these investments since they all have different time frames which makes them incomparable to each other. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"It is then important that we use the present value and not the future value when evaluating these types of investments. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"c5983b89-dff7-4e37-9f6a-139cd3c1463f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","e